[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 9.3: Wound Photography Measurement
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Simple-Medium · **Phase:** MVP · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.02-0.05 per image
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A home health nurse kneels beside a patient's recliner, peels back a dressing, and looks at a pressure ulcer on the patient's sacrum. She needs to document the wound dimensions. Length, width, depth if she can estimate it. She pulls out a disposable ruler, holds it next to the wound, eyeballs the edges, and writes "4.2 cm x 3.1 cm" in her notes. Tomorrow, a different nurse visits. She measures the same wound and writes "3.8 cm x 3.5 cm." Did the wound shrink in one direction and grow in another overnight? Almost certainly not. Two humans just measured the same irregular shape differently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the state of wound measurement in most healthcare settings. Manual ruler-based measurement is the standard of care, and it's terrible. Studies have shown inter-rater variability of 20-40% for the same wound measured by different clinicians. That's not measurement error in the statistical sense. That's noise so large it drowns out the signal you're trying to detect: is this wound healing?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The stakes are real. Chronic wounds affect roughly 6.5 million patients in the United States. Pressure ulcers, diabetic foot ulcers, venous leg ulcers, surgical wound complications. Treatment decisions (change the dressing protocol, refer to a wound care specialist, consider surgical debridement, adjust offloading) depend on whether the wound is getting better or worse. If your measurement tool has 30% noise, you can't detect a 15% improvement. You're flying blind.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Wound photography with automated measurement solves this by replacing the subjective ruler-and-eyeball approach with computer vision. Take a standardized photo, let an algorithm identify the wound boundary and compute the area. Same algorithm, same boundary detection logic, every time. The measurement becomes reproducible. Trends become visible. Healing trajectories become trackable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The technology is mature enough to be useful today, but there are real challenges that aren't obvious until you try to deploy it. Let's dig in.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: How Computers Measure Wounds from Photos
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Image Segmentation: Finding the Wound Boundary
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The core technical problem is image segmentation: given a photograph of a wound, identify which pixels belong to the wound and which belong to surrounding healthy tissue.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This sounds straightforward until you actually look at wound photographs. Wound beds are not uniform. A single wound might contain granulation tissue (red, bumpy), slough (yellow, stringy), necrotic tissue (black, leathery), and epithelializing edges (pink, smooth). The boundary between "wound" and "not wound" is often gradual, not a crisp line. Periwound skin might be macerated, erythematous, or discolored in ways that blur the visual distinction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Modern wound segmentation uses deep learning, specifically encoder-decoder architectures like U-Net and its variants. The encoder compresses the image into a feature representation that captures texture, color, and spatial patterns. The decoder expands that representation back to pixel-level predictions: wound or not-wound for every pixel in the image. The model is trained on thousands of wound photographs where clinicians have manually traced the wound boundary (the "ground truth" annotations).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The output is a binary mask: a same-sized image where wound pixels are 1 and background pixels are 0. From that mask, you can compute area (count the wound pixels), perimeter (trace the boundary), and bounding dimensions (length and width of the smallest enclosing rectangle or ellipse).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Scale Problem: Pixels to Centimeters
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's the thing that makes wound measurement fundamentally different from generic image segmentation: you need real-world units. Knowing that a wound is 50,000 pixels tells you nothing clinically useful. You need to know it's 4.2 square centimeters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Converting pixels to physical units requires a known reference in the image. There are three common approaches:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Physical reference marker.** Place a calibration sticker, ruler, or standardized color card next to the wound before photographing. The system detects the marker, measures its pixel dimensions, and computes a pixels-per-centimeter ratio. This is the most accurate approach. It's also the most annoying for clinicians because they have to remember to include the marker and position it correctly (flat, in the same plane as the wound surface, not at an angle).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured light or depth sensing.** Some specialized wound cameras project a known pattern (dots, grid lines) onto the wound surface. The distortion of the pattern encodes depth and distance information, allowing 3D reconstruction. This gives you area measurements that account for wound curvature and depth. It's more accurate than 2D photography for deep or irregularly shaped wounds. It requires specialized hardware.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Known camera distance.** If you fix the camera-to-wound distance (using a standoff device or a fixed-focus attachment), you can pre-calibrate the pixel-to-centimeter ratio. This is less flexible but eliminates the need for a physical marker in every image. It breaks if the clinician doesn't maintain the correct distance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For most deployments, the physical reference marker approach wins on the balance of accuracy, cost, and hardware simplicity. You're asking clinicians to stick a small adhesive ruler next to the wound. It's one extra step, but it's the difference between a measurement and a guess.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Longitudinal Tracking: The Real Value
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A single wound measurement is useful for documentation. A series of measurements over time is where the clinical value lives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Wound healing follows predictable trajectories. A wound that's going to heal typically shows measurable area reduction within the first 2-4 weeks. The "percent area reduction" (PAR) at week 4 is a validated predictor of eventual healing. If a wound hasn't reduced by at least 40% in area by week 4, it's unlikely to heal with the current treatment plan and should be escalated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This kind of trajectory analysis requires consistent, comparable measurements. If measurement A was taken at 30 cm distance and measurement B at 45 cm distance, and neither included a reference marker, you can't meaningfully compare them. Standardization of the capture protocol is as important as the algorithm itself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The system needs to handle:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Registration:** Matching today's photo to last week's photo of the same wound, even if the angle or framing is slightly different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Normalization:** Ensuring measurements are comparable across sessions (same scale reference, similar lighting).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Trend computation:** Calculating area change, perimeter change, and healing rate over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Alerting:** Flagging wounds that aren't following expected healing trajectories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Color Analysis: Beyond Geometry
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Advanced wound assessment goes beyond size measurement into tissue composition analysis. The color of wound tissue correlates with healing status:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Red (granulation):** Healthy healing tissue. Good sign.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Yellow (slough):** Devitalized tissue that needs debridement. Concerning if increasing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Black (necrotic/eschar):** Dead tissue. Needs intervention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Pink (epithelializing):** New skin forming at wound edges. Excellent sign.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Color-based tissue classification (sometimes called the "RYB" or "Red-Yellow-Black" model) can be automated using the same segmentation approach: train a model to classify wound pixels into tissue types, then compute the percentage of each type. A wound transitioning from 60% yellow/40% red to 20% yellow/80% red is responding to treatment, even if the area hasn't changed much yet.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The challenge: color perception depends heavily on lighting conditions. The same wound tissue looks different under fluorescent lights, natural daylight, and LED flash. Color calibration (using a standardized color card in the image) helps, but doesn't fully solve the problem. This is why tissue classification is a "nice to have" extension rather than a core requirement for the initial system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Makes This Hard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Wound boundary ambiguity.** Where exactly does the wound end and periwound skin begin? Clinicians disagree. Your model will learn whatever consensus (or lack thereof) exists in your training data. For wounds with diffuse edges (like some venous ulcers), there's genuine clinical ambiguity that no algorithm can resolve.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Lighting variation.** Home health visits happen in living rooms with whatever lighting exists. Hospital wound clinics have controlled lighting. The same wound looks dramatically different under warm incandescent light vs. cool fluorescent light vs. camera flash. Your model needs to be robust to these variations, or your capture protocol needs to standardize lighting (which is hard in home health settings).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Anatomical location challenges.** A wound on a flat surface (anterior shin) is easy to photograph perpendicular to the surface. A wound in a body fold (groin, between toes), on a curved surface (heel), or in a hard-to-reach location (sacrum, posterior) is much harder to photograph consistently. Perspective distortion from non-perpendicular angles introduces measurement error.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient population diversity.** Wound appearance varies with skin tone. Erythema (redness indicating inflammation) is visually obvious on light skin and much harder to detect on dark skin. Granulation tissue color varies. Your training data needs to represent the full range of skin tones in your patient population, or your model will perform worse for darker-skinned patients. This is a known bias risk in dermatology and wound care AI.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Reference marker compliance.** In a perfect world, every wound photo includes a properly positioned calibration marker. In reality, clinicians forget, the marker falls off, it's positioned at an angle, or it's partially obscured by the wound dressing. Your system needs graceful degradation: if no marker is detected, flag the image for manual review rather than producing an unreliable measurement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Capture with Reference] → [Detect Marker / Calibrate Scale] → [Segment Wound] → [Compute Measurements] → [Store with Metadata] → [Track Over Time]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Capture with Reference.** A clinician photographs the wound with a calibration marker placed adjacent to it. The capture device can be a smartphone, tablet, or dedicated wound camera. The system should validate image quality before accepting it (is it in focus? is the marker visible? is the wound fully in frame?).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Detect Marker / Calibrate Scale.** The system locates the reference marker in the image and computes the pixels-per-centimeter ratio. If using a standardized marker (like a circular sticker of known diameter), this is a straightforward object detection task. If the marker isn't detected, the image is flagged.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Segment Wound.** A trained segmentation model identifies wound pixels. The output is a binary mask plus optional tissue classification overlay.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compute Measurements.** From the segmentation mask and the calibration ratio: area (in cm²), maximum length, maximum width perpendicular to length, perimeter. Optionally: tissue composition percentages.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Store with Metadata.** The measurement, the segmentation mask, the original image, and metadata (patient ID, wound location, date, clinician, device) are stored together. The image and mask are retained for audit and reprocessing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Track Over Time.** Measurements are linked to a wound timeline. Healing rate is computed. Alerts fire if healing stalls or reverses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Rekognition Custom Labels for wound segmentation.** Rekognition Custom Labels lets you train a custom image classification or object detection model without managing ML infrastructure. For wound segmentation specifically, you'd train a model to detect and localize wound regions. For pixel-level segmentation (which gives you more precise area measurements), you'd use Amazon SageMaker with a U-Net architecture. The choice depends on your accuracy requirements: bounding-box detection is simpler to train but less precise; pixel segmentation is more accurate but requires more annotated training data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and hosting.** If you need pixel-level segmentation (and for clinical wound measurement, you do), SageMaker provides the training infrastructure for U-Net or similar architectures, plus real-time inference endpoints for serving predictions. SageMaker's built-in algorithms include semantic segmentation, and you can bring your own model code for custom architectures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for image storage.** Wound photographs are PHI. They need encrypted, durable, auditable storage. S3 with SSE-KMS, versioning enabled, and lifecycle policies for retention compliance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** The measurement pipeline (receive image, detect marker, call segmentation endpoint, compute measurements, store results) is a stateless workflow that fits Lambda's execution model. For real-time use (clinician takes photo, wants measurement back in seconds), Lambda behind API Gateway provides the synchronous path.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for measurement storage.** Wound measurements are time-series data keyed by patient and wound identifier. DynamoDB's partition key (patient_id + wound_id) and sort key (measurement_date) model fits naturally. Point lookups for the latest measurement and range queries for healing trajectory are both efficient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring.** Track inference latency, segmentation confidence scores, marker detection failure rates, and image quality rejection rates. Alert on degradation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[📱 Clinician Device] -->|Upload wound photo| B[API Gateway]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B --> C[Lambda: Orchestrator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Store original| D[S3: wound-images/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Detect reference marker| E[Lambda: Marker Detection]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Scale factor| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Segment wound| F[SageMaker Endpoint: U-Net]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Segmentation mask| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Compute area, dimensions| G[Lambda: Measurement Calculator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Structured results| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Store measurement| H[DynamoDB: wound-measurements]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Return results| B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I[CloudWatch] -.->|Monitor| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I -.->|Monitor| F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style D fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style H fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Services | S3, Lambda, API Gateway, SageMaker, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, IAM |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | IAM Permissions | s3:PutObject, s3:GetObject, sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint, dynamodb:PutItem, dynamodb:Query, logs:CreateLogGroup |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | BAA | Required. Wound photographs are PHI. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Encryption | S3 SSE-KMS, DynamoDB encryption at rest, TLS 1.2+ in transit |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | VPC | SageMaker endpoint in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | CloudTrail | Enabled for all API calls. Audit trail for PHI access. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Sample Data | Public wound image datasets exist (Medetec, AZH Wound Database). Never use real patient images in development. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost Estimate | ~$0.02-0.05 per image (SageMaker inference dominates). SageMaker endpoint: ~$0.05/hr for ml.m5.large. At 1000 images/day, ~$50-150/month total. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role in This Recipe |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|-------------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon S3 | Encrypted storage for wound images and segmentation masks |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Lambda | Orchestration, marker detection, measurement computation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon API Gateway | REST endpoint for clinician-facing applications |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon SageMaker | Hosts trained U-Net segmentation model for inference |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon DynamoDB | Stores structured measurements and wound timelines |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon CloudWatch | Monitoring, alerting on confidence degradation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS KMS | Encryption key management for PHI at rest |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code (Pseudocode Walkthrough)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 1: Receive and Validate the Wound Image
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The clinician's app uploads a wound photograph. Before we do anything expensive (like calling a ML model), we validate that the image is usable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step, you'll waste inference costs on blurry photos, images without reference markers, and accidental screenshots of the clinician's home screen.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION validate_wound_image(image_bytes, metadata):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check basic image properties
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image = decode_image(image_bytes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF image.width < 640 OR image.height < 640:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN error("Image resolution too low for reliable measurement")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF image.file_size > 20_MB:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN error("Image too large, compress before upload")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check that required metadata is present
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF metadata.patient_id IS MISSING:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN error("Patient ID required")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF metadata.wound_location IS MISSING:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN error("Wound anatomical location required")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store the original image in S3 with metadata
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     s3_key = "wound-images/{patient_id}/{wound_id}/{timestamp}.jpg"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     upload_to_s3(bucket="wound-images", key=s3_key, body=image_bytes,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  metadata=metadata, encryption="aws:kms")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN success(s3_key)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 2: Detect the Reference Marker and Compute Scale
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The reference marker is how we convert pixels to centimeters. Without it, we have a pretty picture but no measurement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step, your "measurements" are just pixel counts with no physical meaning. They can't be compared across sessions taken at different distances.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION detect_reference_marker(image):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Look for the calibration marker (e.g., a circular sticker of known diameter)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This could be a simple color/shape detection or a trained detector
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Approach: detect circular object of expected color (e.g., blue circle, 2.5cm diameter)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     circles = detect_circles(image, color_range="blue",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                             min_radius_px=20, max_radius_px=200)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF no circles found:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN warning("No reference marker detected. Image flagged for manual review.")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Take the best candidate (highest confidence, most circular)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     marker = circles[0]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Known marker diameter = 2.5 cm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Measured marker diameter in pixels = marker.diameter_px
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pixels_per_cm = marker.diameter_px / 2.5
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Sanity check: reasonable range is 10-100 pixels per cm for typical photos
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF pixels_per_cm < 10 OR pixels_per_cm > 100:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN warning("Scale factor outside expected range. Check marker positioning.")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN success(pixels_per_cm, marker.location)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 3: Segment the Wound
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is where the ML model does its work. We send the image to our trained segmentation model and get back a pixel-level mask identifying wound tissue.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step, you're back to manual tracing, which is what we're trying to replace.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION segment_wound(image, sagemaker_endpoint):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Preprocess: resize to model's expected input size, normalize pixel values
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     preprocessed = resize(image, target_size=(512, 512))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     preprocessed = normalize_pixels(preprocessed, mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                    std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Call SageMaker endpoint
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = invoke_sagemaker_endpoint(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         endpoint_name=sagemaker_endpoint,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         content_type="application/x-image",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         body=preprocessed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Response is a probability mask (0.0 to 1.0 per pixel)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     probability_mask = parse_response(response)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Threshold to binary mask
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     binary_mask = probability_mask > 0.5
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute confidence: average probability of wound pixels
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     confidence = mean(probability_mask[binary_mask == True])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF confidence < 0.7:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         flag_for_review("Low segmentation confidence")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Resize mask back to original image dimensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     final_mask = resize(binary_mask, target_size=image.dimensions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN final_mask, confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 4: Compute Wound Measurements
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m With the segmentation mask and the scale factor, we can compute clinically meaningful measurements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step, you have a segmentation mask but no numbers for the clinical record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION compute_measurements(segmentation_mask, pixels_per_cm):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Count wound pixels to get area
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     wound_pixel_count = count(segmentation_mask == True)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     area_px = wound_pixel_count
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     area_cm2 = area_px / (pixels_per_cm * pixels_per_cm)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Find wound boundary contour
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     contour = find_contour(segmentation_mask)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute perimeter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     perimeter_px = contour.length
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     perimeter_cm = perimeter_px / pixels_per_cm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Fit minimum bounding rectangle for length and width
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     bounding_rect = minimum_area_rectangle(contour)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     length_cm = bounding_rect.long_side / pixels_per_cm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     width_cm = bounding_rect.short_side / pixels_per_cm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute circularity (how round is the wound? 1.0 = perfect circle)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     circularity = (4 * PI * area_px) / (perimeter_px * perimeter_px)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "area_cm2": round(area_cm2, 2),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "length_cm": round(length_cm, 2),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "width_cm": round(width_cm, 2),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "perimeter_cm": round(perimeter_cm, 2),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "circularity": round(circularity, 3),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "pixels_per_cm": pixels_per_cm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 5: Store Measurement and Update Wound Timeline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Each measurement becomes a data point in the wound's healing timeline. We store it with enough context to support trend analysis and audit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step, you lose the longitudinal tracking that makes automated measurement valuable over manual documentation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_measurement(patient_id, wound_id, measurements, metadata, image_key, mask_key):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     record = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "patient_id": patient_id,                    // Partition key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "wound_id#timestamp": wound_id + "#" + now(), // Sort key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "wound_id": wound_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "measurement_date": now(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "area_cm2": measurements.area_cm2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "length_cm": measurements.length_cm,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "width_cm": measurements.width_cm,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "perimeter_cm": measurements.perimeter_cm,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "circularity": measurements.circularity,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "confidence": measurements.confidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "image_s3_key": image_key,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "mask_s3_key": mask_key,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "clinician_id": metadata.clinician_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "wound_location": metadata.wound_location,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "device_info": metadata.device_info,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "pixels_per_cm": measurements.pixels_per_cm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     dynamodb.put_item(table="wound-measurements", item=record)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute healing rate if previous measurements exist
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     previous = dynamodb.query(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         table="wound-measurements",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         partition_key=patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sort_key_begins_with=wound_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         limit=1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         scan_index_forward=False  // Most recent first
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF previous exists:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         days_elapsed = (now() - previous.measurement_date).days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF days_elapsed > 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             area_change_pct = ((measurements.area_cm2 - previous.area_cm2)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                               / previous.area_cm2) * 100
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             healing_rate_cm2_per_day = (previous.area_cm2 - measurements.area_cm2)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                       / days_elapsed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Alert if wound is growing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF area_change_pct > 10:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 send_alert("Wound {wound_id} for patient {patient_id} "
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                           "has increased {area_change_pct}% since last measurement")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN record
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter09.03-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Sample output from a successful wound measurement:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "measurement_id": "meas_20260531_143022_abc123",
